1187160	1187160	urn:lsid:Coreoidea.speciesfile.org:TaxonName:458122	1187160	1187118	Spartocera	Laporte. 1832. Essai d'une classification systématique de l'ordre des Hémiptères (Hémiptères Hétéroptères, Latr.). Magasin de Zoologie (Mag. Zoo.) 1-88, plates 51-55	genus	Laporte, 1832	valid		Laporte described the genus Spartocera simultaneously with its subgenus Menenotus but mentioned only one species: Spartocera (Menenotus) lunatus Laporte. It can be argued that the genus Spartocera is monobasic and has the same type species as the subgenus Menenotus. That seems absurd: Laporte clearly excluded lunatus from the nominate subgenus, leaving it without any included species. The next reviser was Burmeister, 1835, who changed the spelling to Spartocerus and included four species. He indicated that he considered his section Ba to be equivalent to Laporte’s Spartocera, placing two species in it: geniculatus ‘Klug’ and lunatus.  Section Ba was in turn divided into two sections, a and ß, with ß indicated as equivalent to Laporte’s subgenus Menenotus. It follows that geniculatus is the first species to be placed in the nominate subgenus (a) Spartocera and is its type species by subsequent monotypy. That is the situation catalogued by Kirkaldy, 1901c: 219 and accepted by Packauskas. | Coreus confluentus is currently placed in the genus Sagotylus (Acanthocerini) but has been interpreted by some authors, including Stål, 1870 and Bergroth, 1913d, as referring to a species of Spartocera.	2016-06-01T12:01:00

1187468	1187468	urn:lsid:Coreoidea.speciesfile.org:TaxonName:491587	1187468	1230079	Anisoscelis (Anisoscelis) marginellus	Dallas. 1852. 1188712	1188712	urn:lsid:Coreoidea.speciesfile.org:TaxonName:451963	1188712	1188644	Cletus pugnator	Fabricius. 1787. Mantissa insectorum sistens species nuper detectas adjectis synonymis, observationibus, descriptionibus, emendationibus 2:1-382	species	(Fabricius, 1787)	valid		Josifov & Kerzhner, 1978: 162 noted that <i>Cimex pugnator</i> Fabricius was synonymized with <i>Cimex trigonus</i>  (Thunberg, 1783) by Stål, 1873: 78 but they regarded the two species as distinct. The record from China rests on material from Guizhou examined by them; Zheng & Dong, 1995 did not see any material from China and recorded <i>trigonus</i>  from Sri Lanka and eastern India as well as much of SE Asia. Records from tropical Asia for <i>trigonus</i>  and <i>pugnator</i>  are inextricably confused. The names <i>Gonocerus acutus</i>  Dallas, 1852 and <i>Cletus bistillatus</i>  Dohrn, 1860b, cited here in synonymy with <i>Cletus trigonus</i>  (Thunberg, 1783), may refer to this species.	2016-05-10T12:21:00

1188811	1188811	urn:lsid:Coreoidea.speciesfile.org:TaxonName:455974	1188811	1188769	Plinachtus imitator	Reuter. 1891. Griechische Heteroptera gesammelt von E. v. Oertzen und J. Emge. Berliner Entomologische Zeitschrift (Berl. Entomol. Zeit) 36:17-34	species	(Reuter, 1891)	valid		Reuter (1891a: 20) gave almost identical descriptions for <i>Gonocerus insidiator</i> var. <i>imitator</i> and <i>G. acutangulatus</i> (sic) var. <i>simulator</i>. Reuter stated that type material of <i>simulator</i> was ‘in collectione mea’ but did not claim that any material of <i>imitator</i> was in his collection; it was presumably returned to its collector, Emge. The neotype of <i>G. imitator</i> was collected at the type locality of <i>G. acutangulatus</i> var. <i>simulator</i>. An editorial note in Aukema & Rieger, 2006: 80 questions the validity of the NT designation.	2016-06-01T09:56:00

Essai sur les genres d'insectes appartenants à l'ordre des Hémiptères, Lin. ou Rhyngotes, Fab. et à la section des Hétéropères, Dufour 1-383	genus	Spinola, 1837	valid		In his original description, Spinola employed two spellings: Plaxiscelis on page 142 and Plaxyscelis in table 7. In 1850: 81 he employed the spelling Plaiscelis, a typographical error which he corrected to Plaxyscelis in 1852: 177, the same year that Dallas, 1852: 378, 437 used the spelling Plaxiscelis. The first reviser is, therefore, either Dallas, 1852 or Spinola, 1852 and the spelling that should be accepted depends on which of these two works has priority.	2016-05-10T12:21:00

1190701	1190701	urn:lsid:Coreoidea.speciesfile.org:TaxonName:453285	1190701	1190682	Thasus	Stål. 1865. Hemiptera nova vel minus cognita. Annales de la Société Entomologique de France 4 5:163-188	genus	Stål, 1865	valid		The first type species fixation that can be traced for Thasus is gigas, stated by Van Duzee, 1916: 92 to be the 'logotype' (type by subsequent designation); I do not know if Van Duzee actually indicated if the designation was his own, made at that time. There were three species originally included by Stal: heteropus, acutangulus and gigas, so Van Duzee's selection is valid. Clearly, O'Shea was unaware of Van Duzee's action and attempted to fix a different species. Van Duzee's designation has priority.	2016-05-10T12:22:00

1191589	1191589	urn:lsid:Coreoidea.speciesfile.org:TaxonName:185744	1191589	1186236	Stenocephalidae	Dallas. 1852. List of the specimens of hemipterous insects in the collection of the British Museum, Taylor & Francis Incorporated, London II:369-592	family	Dallas, 1852	valid		The first name used for this distinctive genus was the vernacular and therefore nomenclaturally unavailable ‘Sténocéphale’ of Latreille, 1825. Latreille, 1829a: 633 published the available Latin form Stenocephalus and this was the name used throughout the nineteenth century. Kirkaldy, 1906: 256 catalogued Berthold’s earlier (1827) Latinisation Stenocephala. Bergroth, 1913e: 12, 1913d: 157-158 noted that Stenocephala had priority over Stenocephalus and adopted it in its stead. Dicranocephalus Hahn, 1826 went unused, despite its claim to priority, even though Westwood, 1840a: 123 had noted that it was synonymous with Stenocephalus. It was not until Stichel, 1935: 357 revived Dicranocephalus in a work on the German fauna that this name began to win acceptance.	2016-11-30T09:10:00
